<p class="Normal" xmlns:news="http://www.dotnetnuke.com/modules/news" xmlns:newsext="urn:NewsExtensions">Using a probation period to assess the suitability of new hires is an outdated practice that could prove legally costly for your company, according to experts, because such a period may create an expectation of a permanent job once probation is completed.<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/shrm/hrnews/~4/iq2y-nT6ygA" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></p>
